SIMPLE: fame
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fame
<hw>Fame</hw> <pr>(f⟦amac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>fame</ets>, L. <ets>fama</ets>, fr. <ets>fari</ets> to speak, akin
to Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/ a saying, report, <grk>fa`nai</grk> to speak. See
<er>Ban</er>, and cf. <er>Fable</er>, <er>Fate</er>, <er>Euphony</er>,
<er>Blame</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Public report or
rumor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>fame</qex> thereof was heard in Pharaoh's house.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xlv. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Report or opinion generally diffused; renown; public
estimation; celebrity, either favorable or unfavorable; <as>as, the
<ex>fame</ex> of <persfn>Washington</persfn></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I find thou art no less than <qex>fame</qex> hath bruited.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Notoriety; celebrity; renown;
reputation.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fame</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fame
<hw>Fame</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Famed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>,; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Faming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To report widely or
honorably.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The field where thou art <qex>famed</qex>⟦br⟧
To have wrought such wonders.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make famous or renowned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those Hesperian gardens <qex>famed</qex> of old.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fameless</ent>⟦br⟧
